DISMISSAL OF POSTMASTER OF WHEAT- LEY RIVER.

Mr. A. A. McLEAN asked: -

1. Was James Power, postmaster at Wheat- ley River, Prince Edward Island, dismissed from oﬂice? It so, on whose recommendation, and for what cause '2

2. Were any charges for inefﬁciency or other- wise made against him 'I

3. Who is his successor, mended his appointment?

4. What was the date or the appointment to ofﬁce of James Power, and what was the date of his dismissal?

5. Did the Governor in Council, or the Post- master General, receive anyapetition or peti< tions for the reinstatement of the said James Power ‘2

6. What action. if any, has been taken on said petitions? .

7. Has any inquiry into the matter been or- dered, or is any in contemplation ?

Hon. Sir WILLIAM MULOCK (Postmas- ter General). 011 the 12th January, 1905, the department decided to remove Mr. James Power from the position of postmaster at Wheatley River which oﬂice he had held since prior to 1873, the reason for his re- moval being that during the last Dominion election he had proved himself an active, oﬁensive, political partisan, among other things taking part in public speaking on be- half of one of the candidates, and otherwise acting throughout the campaign as a poli- tical partisan. On the 1st of February a petition was received at the department ask— ing for his retention, but the request was not acceded to, some weeks before the post- master having been notiﬁed of his dismissal. Action was based upon reliable information as to the accuracy of the charges and no‘ further inquiry into the matter is considered necessary.
